Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden faces a critical decision: Who should he appoint as head of the US Federal Reserve – that is, to the possibly most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have serious consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to properly regulate the banking system, thereby setting the stage for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political leaders' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of dissatisfaction among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a variety of stereotypes or reasons why the current Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell should be reappointed.
It would be a demonstration of bipartisan appeal.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
Someone with experience would be needed to guide us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
Exactly the same arguments I heard 25 years ago, when I was chairman of President Bill Clinton's economic advisory staff and the confirmation of Greenspan was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid a high price for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and denied Volcker a second term after he had tamed inflation.
Reagan owed Volcker a lot, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, a follower of Ayn Rand.
In economic policy, careful judgment and sensitivity to conflicting objectives are required.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and competitive on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always held clearly articulated, but distinctly different, views on these issues (at least until the Republicans fell into populist frenzy).
In my view, Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis showed that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, only in tight labor markets are marginalized groups integrated into the economy and wage disparities reduced.
The coming years are likely to be a test for any US central bank chair.
Already now, the US is facing difficult decisions on what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially a minor problem caused by an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed view the unemployment rate among African Americans, which has not yet returned to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and the resulting increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the mispricing of mortgage-backed securities for the 2008 crisis played a central role, there are now indications of a stronger and more widespread mispricing of climate-related assets.
What should the Fed do in this regard?
Powell is not the man of the hour.
First, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and thereby risked the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take action regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers around the world have since declared this to be the central issue of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues do not belong to the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's mandate to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater threat to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's record in this area suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
Such laxity is the last thing the economy needs right now.
An obvious lack of competition and the absence of sufficient regulation already allow excessive profits, reduce lending to small businesses, and give dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators credit Powell for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
Yet any second-year student would have known that during a recession, you must not tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT argues, Powell does not feel particularly strongly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board, regarding the tightening of monetary policy over the past decade, was marked by a series of misjudgments that date back to the "Taper Tantrum" of 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the Fed's concern, it is a fact that the bank's policies have significant distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early rate hike can stifle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act allows for stronger concentrations of market power.
And finally, the recent scandal involving stock trading by senior Fed officials has undermined confidence in the leadership of the central bank.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including in the administration of certain Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has long been a concern for me.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in U.S. institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the central bank's integrity will suffer further.
No Fed official should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock trades would appear inappropriate.
The Fed is somewhat similar to the U.S. Supreme Court.
This body is supposed to be above politics, but at least since Bush v. Gore, we know that is not the case.
Trump made this clear for all who still had doubts.
Even the Fed is supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is not the case either, by following their party's deregulation agenda.
Yet while the Federal Reserve Board makes important decisions that affect all aspects of the economy, power has traditionally concentrated in the hands of the Fed chairman – much more so than with the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the Fed chairman who decides what issues come up for vote and which topics are postponed or prioritized.
The climate issue is just one example where it is enormously important who sits at the head of the table.
The United States needs a central bank that truly commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Anyone who believes that we can rely on unregulated markets or that regulation has already gone too far lacks insight.
We don't need an ideologue like Greenspan or a Wall Street-friendly lawyer like Powell.
We need someone with deep economic understanding who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't need to look far to find someone who has already demonstrated their capabilities.
Lael Brainard is already on the Federal Reserve Board, where she has demonstrated her expertise and gained the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a female Fed chairman who maintains continuity and does not disrupt the markets, but who also shares his economic and social agenda.
